<P>AN ENQUIRY INTO, AND OBSERVATIONS UPON THE CAUSES AND EFFECTS OF THE <HI>EPIDEMIC DISEASE,</HI> WHICH RAGED IN PHILADELPHIA FROM THE MONTH OF AUGUST TILL TOWARDS THE MIDDLE OF DECEMBER, 1793.</P>
<P>BY JEAN DEVEZE, MASTER IN SURGERY, FROM CAPE FRAN&Ccedil;AIS, PHYSICIAN OF THE HOSPITAL AT BUSH-HILL, SURGEON-MAJOR AND PRINCIPAL PHY|SICIAN OF THE MILITARY HOSPITAL ESTABLISHED BY THE FRENCH REPUBLIC AT PHILADELPHIA.</P>
<Q>Nature is the fir&s;t Phy&s;ician.
<BIBL>HYPPOCRATES, Pop. Mal. b. 6, s. 5.</BIBL></Q>
<P>PRINTED BY PARENT, PHILADELPHIA. 1794.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="to the reader">
<PB REF="026873_0002_0FD242F5686D26D0">
<HEAD>ADVERTISEMENT.</HEAD>
<P>THE epidemic di&s;ea&s;e, of which &s;o many of the citizens of Philadelphia fell victims, and which &s;pread &s;uch a &s;cene of terror around it by its ravages in the month of Augu&s;t, intere&s;ted the feelings of the compa&s;&s;ionate &s;o forcibly, that at their own expence the ho&s;pital at Bu&s;h-hill was opened.</P>
<P>At this juncture I arrived on this continent, and was appointed to the medical direction of this ho&s;pital. As the patients multiplied in abundance, Dr. Benjamin Duffield, a member of the College of Phy&s;icians of this city, was a&s;&s;ociated with me by the committee. My fir&s;t care was to communicate to him my mode of treat|ment, and my rea&s;ons for adopting the various methods I had cho&s;en to encounter the de&s;tructive plague which depopulated the city, and overwhelmed it with melan|choly and con&s;ternation. Dr. Duffield, after having examined my practice, and vi&s;ited the patients with me in concert, a&s;&s;ured me that his mode of treatment was entirely conformable to mine, and that he &s;hould co|incide in the plan I had e&s;tabli&s;hed without alteration.</P>
<P>The approbation of a profe&s;&s;ional man, who&s;e repu|tation alone &s;peaks his eulogy, and who to his intelli|gence in medicine joins the &s;ucce&s;sful practice of &s;urgery,
<PB N="iv" REF="026873_0004_0FD242FBCD070D70">
was, I confe&s;s, to me a motive of encouragement. Be|&s;ides, I had per&s;uaded my&s;elf, that I had fallen upon the true indications of cure; and therefore continued my treatment according to my principles, excepting only in tho&s;e ca&s;es in which particular circum&s;tances required its modification.</P>
<P>The harmony which perpetually &s;ub&s;i&s;ted between, Dr. Duffield and my&s;elf, did not a little contribute without doubt, to the &s;ucce&s;s we experienced in the management of a di&s;ea&s;e, one of the mo&s;t de&s;tructive that the human race can be afflicted with. This &s;ucce&s;s was another motive for me to be particular and exact in the ob&s;ervations I have now the honour to pre&s;ent to the public. They were originally de&s;tined to re|main buried in my port-folio, for my own u&s;e, and to have recour&s;e to in cafe of nece&s;&s;ity, if ever the &s;ame di&s;ea&s;e &s;hould again appear with the &s;ame &s;ymptoms and variations.</P>
<P>But I could not re&s;i&s;t the &s;olicitation of &s;ome particu|lar friends; and I moreover imagined that they might be u&s;eful to profe&s;&s;ional gentlemen who have not had an opportunity of following the di&s;ea&s;e through all its modifications, and to whom the danger of experiments and endeavours, always painful and afflicting to huma|nity, has been di&s;pen&s;ed with. I had another motive, which was to incite tho&s;e to whom the di&s;ea&s;e was already known, to execute better than my&s;elf the de&s;ire I had of being u&s;eful.<PB N="vi" REF="026873_0006_0FD243005F5CABD8">
Added to this, &s;ome directors of the ho&s;pital, and the committee to whom its admini&s;tration was intru&s;ted, have informed me, that they &s;hould with plea&s;ure &s;ee my ob&s;ervations publi&s;hed. I therefore thought it a duty to yield to their reque&s;t, and to gratify my own feelings in this te&s;timony of my e&s;teem for them. If my endeavours have been u&s;eful, it is in part owing to the encouragement they in&s;pired me with, and to the example they placed before my eyes, in performing with the mo&s;t religious pity, the mo&s;t meritorious acts of benevolence and charity. I dare then to flatter my|&s;elf, that the&s;e motives which have in&s;pired me, rather than the de&s;ire of book-making, will be a &s;ufficient excu&s;e for the faults which will nece&s;&s;arily be found in this performance, and will obtain the indulgence of the reader, who will neither find that elegance and correct|ne&s;s of &s;tile &s;o nece&s;&s;ary in works of entertainment, and &s;o &s;uperfluous when &s;imple facts are to be narrated.</P>
<P>If the&s;e re&s;earches and ob&s;ervations on the cau&s;es, qualities, and treatment of the di&s;ea&s;e which was their object, &s;hould meet with any contradictions, or per&s;ons of a different opinion, I now, once for all, declare that I renounce all controver&s;y.</P>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 LANG="fre" TYPE="version">
<DIV2 TYPE="to the reader">
<PB REF="026873_0003_0FD242FA05345A08">
<HEAD>AVERTISSEMENT.</HEAD>
<P>LES ravages qu'occa&s;ionnalt en Ao&ucirc;t dernier, dans la ville de Philadelphie, la maladie &eacute;pid&eacute;mique, dont tant de citoyens ont &eacute;t&eacute; les victimes, et qui a r&eacute;pandu tant de terreur, ont int&eacute;re&s;&s;&eacute; l'humanit&eacute; de quelques ames compati&s;&s;antes qui ont fond&eacute; &agrave; leurs frais l'h&ocirc;pital qui &s;ub&s;i&s;te encore &s;ous le nom de Bush-hill.</P>
<P>J'arriva<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">s &agrave; cette &eacute;poque dans ce continent; je &s;us choi&s;i pour avoir la direction de cet h&ocirc;pital, en qualit&eacute; de m&eacute;decin. Comme les malades y abondaient, le comit&eacute; m'a&s;&s;ocia le docteur Benjamin Duffield, membre du col|l&eacute;ge de m&eacute;decine de cette ville. Mon premier <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">oin fut de lui communiquer la mani&egrave;re dont je fai&s;ais u&s;age, et les motifs qui d&eacute;terminai<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">nt mon choix pour chacun des moyens que j'adoptais afin de combattre le fl&eacute;au de&s;tructeur qui d&eacute;peuplait la ville, et r&eacute;pandait par|tout la tri&s;te&s;&s;e et la con&s;ternation. M. Duffield, apr&egrave;s avoir examin&eacute; ma pratique et vi&s;it&eacute; les malades avec moi, approuva ma mani&egrave;re, me dit que la &s;ienne &eacute;tait en|ti&egrave;rement conforme, et qu'il adoptait le plan de traite|ment que j'avais &eacute;tabli, &s;ans propo&s;er aucun changement.</P>
<P>L'approbation d'un homme de l'art, dont la r&eacute;pu|tation &s;eule fait l'&eacute;loge, et qui joint aux connai&s;&s;ances de la m&eacute;decine celles de la chirurgie qu'il exerce avec les m&ecirc;mes &s;ucc&egrave;s, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ut pour moi, je l'avoue, un motif d'encouragement; je me per&s;uadai d'autant plus d'avoir &s;ai&s;i les vraies indications curatives. Je continual donc les traitemen<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> d'apr&egrave;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> mes principes, &s;auf les modifi|cations
<PB N="v" REF="026873_0005_0FD242FF12889D18">
dont les circon&s;tances d&eacute;terminaient la n&eacute;ce&s;&s;i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">. La bonne intelligence qui n'a ce&s;&s;&eacute; de r&eacute;gner entre le docteur Duffield et moi, n'a pas peu contribu&eacute;, &s;ans doute, aux &s;ucc&egrave;s que nous avons obtenus dans le trai|tement d'une maladie des plus meurtri&egrave;res, dont l'e&s;|p&egrave;ce humaine pui&s;&s;e &ecirc;tre afflig&eacute;e. Ces &s;ucc&egrave;s ont &eacute;t&eacute; pour moi un motif de plus pour mettre quelque clart&eacute; dans les ob&s;ervations que je pr&eacute;&s;ente au|jourd'hui au public. Elles n'&eacute;taient d'abord de&s;tin&eacute;es qu'&agrave; demeurer en&s;evelies dans mon porte-feuille, pour moi &s;eul et pour les con&s;ulter au be&s;oin, quant &agrave; l'u&s;age des moyens que j'avais employ&eacute;s, &s;i toute <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ois la m&ecirc;me maladie venait &agrave; &s;e reproduire avec les m&ecirc;mes variations et les m&ecirc;mes &s;ympt&ocirc;mes: mais je n'ai pu me refu&s;er &agrave; la &s;ollicitation de quelques amis. J'ai pen&s;&eacute; en outre que, d'une part, elles pourraient &ecirc;tre utiles aux per&s;onnes de l'art qui n'auraient pas eu occa&s;ion d'&eacute;tudier cette maladie et de la &s;uivre dans toutes &s;es modifications, et qui &s;eront di&s;pen&s;&eacute;es du danger des exp&eacute;riences et des e&s;&s;ais toujours f&acirc;cheux et toujours affligeans pour l'humanit&eacute;, et que d'une autre part elles pourront engager ceux &agrave; qui elle &s;erait d&eacute;j&agrave; connue &agrave; remplir mieux que moi le d&eacute;&s;ir que j'ai eu de bien faire.</P>
<P>De plus, quelques directeurs de cet h&ocirc;pital, et le comit&eacute;, &agrave; qui l'admini&s;tration en a &eacute;t&eacute; confi&eacute;e, m'ayant lai&s;&s;&eacute; entrevoir qu'ils verraient avec plai&s;ir mes ob&s;er|vations mi&s;es au jour, j'ai cru devoir c&eacute;der &agrave; ce de&s;ir, et &agrave; la &s;atisfaction que j'&eacute;prouve &agrave; leur en faire l'hom|mage. Si mon z&egrave;le a pu &ecirc;tre utile, je le dois en partie &agrave; l'encouragement qu'ils m'ont in&s;pir&eacute; et &agrave; l'exemple qu'ils m'ont donn&eacute;, les ayant vu remplir avec la pi&eacute;t&eacute; la plus religieu&s;e, les actes de la bienfai&s;ance et de la
<PB N="vii" REF="026873_0007_0FD24304448A3370">
charit&eacute; la plus m&eacute;ritoire. J'o&s;e me flatter que ces motifs auxquels j'ai c&eacute;d&eacute; plut&ocirc;t qu'&agrave; celui de faire un livre, feront pardonner les n&eacute;gligences qui doivent &s;e ren|contrer dans cet &eacute;crit, et m'obtiendront l'indulgence du Lecteur, qui n'y trouvera ni cette &eacute;l&eacute;gance, ni cette correction de &s;tile, &s;i n&eacute;ce&s;&s;aire dans des ouvrages de pur agr&eacute;ment, et &s;i &s;uperflues dans une &s;imple narration de faits.</P>
<P>Si mes recherches et mes ob&s;ervations &s;ur les cau&s;es, les qualit&eacute;s et le traitement de la maladie qui en fait l'objet, rencontraient quelques contradiction ou quel|ques per&s;onnes d'une opinion diff&eacute;rente, je pr&eacute;viens que je renonce d'avance &agrave; toute di&s;cu&s;&s;ion pol&eacute; mique.</P>
</DIV2>
